Student groups and state politicians are criticizing the University of Georgia for not allowing in-person voting on campus this fall.

Meanwhile, thousands of fans are expected to attend UGA's first home football game on October 3. https://t.co/BzNtWvaUU4

text: Attorney General William Barr told top Justice Department prosecutors that he wants them to be aggressive in bringing charges related to protest violence, including exploring using a rarely used sedition law, a source says https://t.co/G6ynh2KyOm

text: The Democratic Party's grassroots campaign renaissance is facing an existential challenge ahead of the November election, with the sharpest tool in organizers' kits — face-to-face meetings at potential voters' doorsteps — blunted by the Covid-19 pandemic https://t.co/1yAWRH0O5G

text: A 12-foot alligator was spotted in Gulf Shores, Alabama, after Hurricane Sally made landfall early Wednesday. "This is why we don't want to go outside," said Tina Lambert Bennett, who filmed the alligator outside her window. https://t.co/MuzaKk1Icz https://t.co/k3ZkzlEm97

text: DNI Ratcliffe reversed course on his decision to end in-person election security briefings for key members of Congress by announcing that the intelligence community will continue to provide lawmakers on relevant oversight committees with in-person updates https://t.co/L4ss5BfYs3
